-Muslim Affairs)}}\n| successor2 = Nolee Ashilin Radzi {{small|(Health)}} <br/> [[Saarani Mohammad|Saarani Mohamad]] {{small|(Local Government)}} <br/> Samsudin Abu Hassan {{small|(Consumer Affairs)}} <br/> Mohd Amin Zakaria {{small|(Environment)}} <br/> [[Zambry Abdul Kadir]] {{small|(Public Transport, Non-Muslim Affairs)}}     \n| constituency2 = [[Chenderiang (state constituency)|Chenderiang]]\n |office3             = Deputy President of [[Malaysian Chinese Association]]\n |term_start3         = 4 November 2018\n |term_end3           = \n |predecessor3        = [[Wee Ka Siong]]\n |president3        = [[Wee Ka Siong]]\n |successor3          =\n\n\n |assembly4        = Perak State Legislative \n |constituency_AM4 = Chenderiang\n |term_start4      = 8 March 2008\n |term_end4        = 9 May 2018\n |majority4        = 3,392 (2008) <br/> 4,467 (2013)\n |predecessor4     = Chan Kon You ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|MCA]] \u2013 [[Barisan Nasional|BN]])\n |successor4       = [[Ahmad Faizal Azumu]] ([[Malaysian Chinese Association|PPBM]] \u2013 [[Pakatan Harapan|PH]])\n |birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1965|07|19|df=y}}\n |birth_place      = [[Changkat Keruing]], [[Perak]], [[Malaysia]]\n |death_date       = \n |death_place      =\n |othername        = \n |nationality      = {{MYS}}\n |party            = [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] (MCA)\n |otherparty       = [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN)\n |sex              = \n |spouse           = Lim Soo Lee\n |children         = 3\n |religion         = \n |profession       = \n |image            = Mah Hang Soon.png\n |alma_mater       = [[Universiti Malaya]]\n}}\n\n[[Malay titles|Dato']] '''Dr Mah Hang Soon''' ({{zh|t=\u99ac\u6f22\u9806|s=\u9a6c\u6c49\u987a}}; born 1965) is a Malaysian politician who is currently serve as deputy president of [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] since 2018. He had served as member of [[Perak State Legislative Assembly]] for Cenderiang from 2008 to 2018. He is appointed by [[Muhyiddin Yassin|Prime Minister]] to be deputy minister in [[Ministry of Education (Malaysia)|Ministry of Education]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/03/10/appreciation-shown-for-mca|publisher=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|title=Appreciation shown on MCA|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nDato' Dr. Mah Hang Soon (1965-present) is a cardiologist and graduate of the [[University of Malaya]]. He has been involved in full-time politics since 2009.\n\nOriginally from Kampung Baru [[Changkat Kruing]], [[Ayer Tawar]], Perak Darul Ridzuan. He is the eldest child of the 6 siblings. His father Mah Chow Nam (1945-2014) and his mother Lee Kee Hiong (1944-present) were smallholders of rubber and oil palm. He married Datin Lim Soo Lee and had a son named Mah Song Wei (1996-present).\n\n==Malaysian Chinese Association (MCA)==\nHe is the current deputy president of MCA. He was previously the National MCA Youth Vice President and the Perak MCA Youth Chief in 2008-2010. From 2013 until now, he is the Chairman of the MCA Perak and the Central Council (CC).\n\n==Political career==\nIn the [[2004 Malaysian general election|11th Malaysian general election]], Dato' Dr. Mah Hang Soon contested the [[Jelapang (state constituency)|Jelapang]] state seat in the Perak State Legislative Assembly. He failed to win by 7,981 votes compared to [[Hee Yit Foong]], a [[Democratic Action Party|DAP]] candidate who gained 8,233 votes.\n\nIn the [[2008 Malaysian general election|12th Malaysian general election]], he won the state assembly for [[Chenderiang (state constituency)|Chenderiang]] state seat with a majority of 3,392 votes and repeated the same victory in the [[2013 Malaysian general election|13th Malaysian general election]] with a majority of 4,767 votes.\n\nDato' Dr. Mah Hang Soon has served as Perak State Assemblyman for his portfolio as follows:\n* Chairman of the Health, Local Government, Consumer Affairs, Environment, Transportation and Non-Muslim Affairs (2009-2013); and\n* Chairman of the Committee on Health, Public Transportation, Non-Islamic Affairs, National Integration and New Villages (2014-2018).\n\nOn April 24, 2018, he was announced as the candidate for the [[Tanjong Malim (federal constituency)|Tanjong Malim]] parliamentary seat for the [[2018 Malaysian general election|14th Malaysian general election]].\n\nHe subsequently received a protest from YB Dato' Sri [[Ong Ka Chuan]]'s supporters and protested in front of the Bangunan Perdana, Putrajaya on April 26, 2018. Finally, the Nomination Session was held at the Tanjong Malim District Council, Tanjong Malim, Perak Darul Ridzuan on April 28, 2018 confirming that Dato' Dr. Mah Hang Soon is contesting in the Tanjong Malim parliamentary seat for GE14.\n\nIn the [[2018 Malaysian general election|14th Malaysian general election]], he lost to the [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) candidate [[Chang Lih Kang]]. The total number of votes he received was 19,314 while the PKR candidate received 24,672 votes with a majority of 5,358 votes. Overall, the [[Barisan Nasional]] lost the parliamentary seat and failed to form the Federal Government in the GE14.\n\n===Election results===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Perak State Legislative Assembly]]'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://keputusan.spr.gov.my|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]]|language=Malay|accessdate=10 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423092454/http://keputusan.spr.gov.my/|archive-date=23 April 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://semak.spr.gov.my/spr/laporan/5_KedudukanAkhir.php|title=Keputusan Pilihan Raya Umum Parlimen/Dewan Undangan Negeri|publisher=[[Election Commission of Malaysia]]|language=Malay|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!